<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Depositors</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One lesson of the Silicon Valley Bank failure =
is that some bank deposits are better than others. Lots of US regional bank=
s were doing more or less the same thing in 2021: They were taking money fr=
om depositors, promising to give it back whenever the depositors wanted, pa=
ying 0% interest on those deposits, and investing the money=C2=A0in long-te=
rm bonds at like 2% interest. Then interest rates went up and those bonds w=
ere worth much less than they used to be. If the depositors all asked for t=
heir money back at the same time, as is their right, the banks would have t=
o sell the bonds at a big loss, leaving them without enough money to pay de=
positors. On the other hand if all the depositors kept their money in the b=
ank as rates went up, without even demanding higher interest rates on their=
 checking accounts, then the bank would be fine. The bank would be great, e=
ven: As rates go up, the bank will earn more on its assets,<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> but it won=E2=80=99t have to pay more to its sleepy and undemanding de=
positors. A bank with sleepy depositors would do well, a bank with antsy de=
positors would go bust, even if their investments were the same.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to say this is that a bank with sleepy=
 and undemanding depositors is much more valuable than a bank with nervous =
and demanding depositors, but it is hard to measure that. In fact bank regu=
lation does=C2=A0<em>try=C2=A0</em>to measure that; it knows that some type=
s of deposits are flightier than others, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/30998985.263439/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmlzLm9yZy9wdWJs=
L2JjYnMyMzguaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB526a7c6d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> liquidity regu=
lations</a> require banks to have more cash to cover flighty=C2=A0deposits =
than stable ones. (For instance, deposits that are not covered by deposit i=
nsurance are flightier than ones that are.) But it is a crude and imprecise=
 approach to a basically social set of questions: What are your depositors =
like? Do they talk to each other? When they get together, do they tend to c=
alm each other down or work each other up?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another way to say it is that a bank=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0<em>assets=C2=A0</em>have some duration =E2=80=94=C2=A0some sensitivi=
ty to interest rates =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is driven mainly by the official t=
erms of those assets: A long-term fixed-rate bond has a lot of duration, a =
floating-rate loan has less. And the bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>liabilities=C2=
=A0</em>have some duration that is driven=C2=A0<em>partly=C2=A0</em>by thei=
r legal terms (if the bank issues long-term bonds, they have a lot of durat=
ion) but mostly by the behavior of their depositors. In some technical sens=
e a checking account has zero duration =E2=80=94=C2=A0the customer can take=
 her money out at any time =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in a practical sense, if all =
your customers keep their money in their checking accounts for years withou=
t even looking at the interest rate, that is very valuable long-term financ=
ing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the idea is basically to match the (a=
ctual, legal) duration of your assets with the (rough, behavioral) duration=
 of your liabilities.=C2=A0But you don=E2=80=99t really <em>know</em>=C2=A0=
the duration of your deposits; you have to estimate it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Silicon Valley Bank took a lot of interest-rat=
e risk with its assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0it bought long-term bonds and <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30998985.263439/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9saXZlY292ZXJhZ2Uvc3RvY2stbWFya2V0LW5ld3MtdG9kYXktMDMtMTMt=
MjAyMy9jYXJkL3NpbGljb24tdmFsbGV5LWJhbmstZHJvcHBlZC1hLWhlZGdlLWFnYWluc3Qtcml=
zaW5nLXJhdGVzLWluLTIwMjItNk1pRDlaTFZZOUNGOHpiSU03emU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB767c45de" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> got rid of its interest-rate hedges</a> =E2=80=94 per=
haps because it thought it had pretty long-lived liabilities. Why not? It i=
nvested a lot in its relationships with its depositor customers =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0Silicon Valley venture capitalists and the tech startups they backed =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and probably figured they were loyal. It took them out to ni=
ce events, it supported them when times were tough, it gave them loans no o=
ne else would give them, it worked with them to find financial solutions, i=
t had good customer service. =E2=80=9COur customers love us and won=E2=80=
=99t leave if some other bank offers them 0.25% higher interest rates,=E2=
=80=9D SVB could reasonably have thought, =E2=80=9Cso it=E2=80=99s fine if =
we put their money in 6-year bonds.=E2=80=9D Also apparently a lot of SVB=
=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>loans=C2=A0</em>to startups contained covenants requiri=
ng the startups to keep their deposits at SVB, so in some rough sense the c=
ustomers <em>couldn=E2=80=99t</em> leave.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The simple story of SVB=E2=80=99s failure is t=
hat it had an asset-liability mismatch: It had all these demand deposits, i=
t used them to buy long-term bonds, and when interest rates went up those b=
onds lost value. But the counterargument would be that SVB thought it=C2=A0=
had long-term liabilities =E2=80=94=C2=A0these locked-in, loyal deposits =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and so matched its assets to its liabilities. When rates wen=
t up, its bonds became less valuable, but its loyal stable deposits became=
=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>valuable: Having cheap funding from loyal customer=
s is even better when interest rates go up. SVB hedged the interest-rate ri=
sk on its bonds by investing in good relationships with its depositors.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This counterargument is not crazy! It just tur=
ned out to be totally wrong. It turned out that SVB=E2=80=99s depositors we=
re not=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>loyal than average bank customers, but <em>l=
ess=C2=A0</em>loyal.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Here is a Bloomberg News story about how <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30998985.263439/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjkvc3ZiLWJhbmstcnVuLWZlYXJzLXN3aXJsZ=
WQtb24tdmMtZm91bmRlci1uZXR3b3Jrcy1iZWZvcmUtaGl0dGluZy10d2l0dGVyP2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDAzMjkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB40d0459f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  the network of SVB customers panicked each other =
into a bank run</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Channels like messaging platform WhatsApp, ema=
il chains, texts and other closed forums were full of chatter over the bank=
=E2=80=99s financial precarity well before those fears showed up Twitter. I=
n tech, where executives=E2=80=99 networks can dictate whether companies ha=
ve access to the best information, warnings about SVB had been simmering fo=
r a while when they boiled over into wider view online.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt wasn=E2=80=99t phone calls; it was=
n=E2=80=99t social media,=E2=80=9D said a Silicon Valley startup founder wh=
o watched the fear escalate that week in March. =E2=80=9CIt was private cha=
t rooms and message groups.=E2=80=9D This person, who requested anonymity d=
iscussing private message conversations, said it was particularly alarming =
to hear from other founders who said they would move their money. =E2=80=A6=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By Thursday, the worry was widespread. On=C2=
=A0a forum for Y Combinator startups, the accelerator=E2=80=99s president G=
arry Tan wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAnytime you hear problems of solvency in any =
bank, and it can be deemed credible, you should take it seriously.=E2=80=9D=
 In an email thread of more than 1,000 founders backed by Andreessen Horowi=
tz, many entrepreneurs were encouraging=C2=A0each other to pull cash from t=
he bank.=C2=A0 David George, a general partner at the firm, weighed in some=
what cryptically: =E2=80=9CHi all, We know you have questions about how to =
handle the SVB situation,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =E2=80=9CWe encourage you to p=
ick up the phone and call your GP.=E2=80=9D ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Matt Murphy, a partner at Menlo Ventures, said=
 his firm alerted its startups late Thursday that a bank run was underway. =
By then, it had become clear to observers. The firm told all its founders t=
o move 30% of their capital to another bank =E2=80=9Cas fast as possible,=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Murphy said. =E2=80=9CWe told every partner to call every CE=
O. For some partners it was five calls, for others it was 14.=E2=80=9D Murp=
hy said the firm opted=C2=A0for phone calls instead of=C2=A0text messages o=
r email in an attempt to have =E2=80=9Ca more calming conversation.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Murphy, the Menlo Ventures investor, still fee=
ls a little shell-shocked by SVB=E2=80=99s collapse. He=C2=A0had been relat=
ively slow to move funds, he said, because up until the final moments=C2=A0=
it was far from clear that the=C2=A0decades-old institution would so swiftl=
y implode. He had served on SVB=E2=80=99s venture capital advisory board fo=
r 20 years, along with a dozen other representatives=C2=A0from elite ventur=
e firms. The quarterly meetings typically focused on a single topic, which =
ranged from VC funding strategies in China to up-and-coming sectors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere would always be great wine and =
great discussions,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Murphy said of the friendly roundtable dis=
cussions, where most top firms were=C2=A0represented.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB had a reasonable model of =E2=80=9Cnetwork=
ing with venture capitalists and making them love us and giving them wine w=
ill make them slow to move their money,=E2=80=9D whereas in fact the right =
model was =E2=80=9Chaving a very networked group of sophisticated customers=
 means that they will be quite quick to move their money.=E2=80=9D Traditio=
nal banks do not have customers who will spring into action to set up a tel=
ephone chain to cause a bank run. But Silicon Valley is efficient and scala=
ble, so they got their money out fast.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand First Republic Bank seems to=
 have basically similar problems to SVB =E2=80=94=C2=A0deposit flight, inte=
rest-rate losses =E2=80=94 and it is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30998985.263439/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTcvYmlnLWJhbmtzLXRydXN0LWZpcnN0LXJlcHVibGljLXd=
pdGgtdGhlaXItbW9uZXk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbW=
FpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb=
25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6cf471ec" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  not exactly in gre=
at shape</a>. But here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/30998985.263439/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjMtMDMtMjkvZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtcy1mcmMtcmljaC12b2NhbC1jbGllbnRzLXRha2=
