<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Schematically, here=E2=80=99s how distressed d=
ebt exchanges work.=C2=A0A company borrows $100 from creditors and then run=
s into trouble. It goes to the creditors and says =E2=80=9Cwe can=E2=80=99t=
 pay you back the $100 we owe you right now, and in fact we need another $2=
0 to keep running our business. Tell you what: You exchange your existing l=
oans for some new loans that mature two years later, and also lend us some =
new cash. In exchange, we=E2=80=99ll give you all of our assets as collater=
al, so if we go bankrupt you=E2=80=99ll get paid off before all of our othe=
r creditors. If you agree to this exchange, you=E2=80=99ll be first in line=
 to get paid. If you don=E2=80=99t agree to the exchange, you can keep your=
 old loans, but you=E2=80=99ll be last in line.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a very general matter, loan and bond docume=
nts will be written in a way that prevents=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>of this =
sort of thing, but not all of it. You do not want to make this too easy for=
 the company, because then paying back the money it owes would be optional;=
 it could always go to creditors and say =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99ll mess up=
 your loans if you don=E2=80=99t extend them,=E2=80=9D and the lenders will=
 grudgingly extend.=C2=A0But you don=E2=80=99t want to make it too hard for=
 the company either, because sometimes the way to create the most value for=
 everyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0including creditors =E2=80=94=C2=A0is to give the =
company a little more breathing room, and you don=E2=80=99t want to give cr=
editors=C2=A0too much leverage to block that. In general some majority or s=
upermajority of the creditors can get together to approve <em>some </em>ver=
sion of this: They might be able to amend the debt documents to allow some =
new loans with higher repayment priority, and then exchange their own loans=
 into those new higher-priority loans.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mechanically, there are two broad ways that th=
is negotiation could go:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company could go to all of its le=
nders and say =E2=80=9Chey we need more time and money, please help us out =
by exchanging into new loans, if you do you=E2=80=99ll be first in line and=
 if you don=E2=80=99t you=E2=80=99ll be last in line.=E2=80=9D And then if =
a majority of the lenders agree, the company gets what it wants and the maj=
ority creditors get new good loans, while the minority creditors keep old b=
ad loans.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company could go to=
=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>of its lenders =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally a majority=
 =E2=80=94 and say =E2=80=9Chey we need more time and money, please help us=
 out by exchanging into new loans, that way you can be first in line and ev=
eryone else can be last in line.=E2=80=9D The majority then exchanges into =
the new good loans; the minority never gets the chance, and is stuck in the=
 bad old loans.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first approach has the advantage of being =
fairer and tidier: You give everyone the opportunity to help the company ou=
t and get the new loans, but you threaten them with the bad loans if they s=
ay no. Everyone has an incentive to approve the deal: If the deal is approv=
ed, it is much better to be a majority lender than a minority one, so every=
one will be tempted to say yes to the exchange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second approach has the advantage of=C2=A0=
<em>transferring value from the minority to the=C2=A0majority</em>, which m=
akes it more appealing to the majority. If you have $100 of debt outstandin=
g and you go to all your lenders and say =E2=80=9Chey please exchange into =
new, higher-priority loans,=E2=80=9D and they all do, then they all have th=
e same priority and nobody is ahead of anybody else. If you go bankrupt and=
 there=E2=80=99s only $60 left, then all the lenders get 60 cents on the do=
llar. If you go to holders of $51 of the loans and say =E2=80=9Chey please =
exchange into new, higher-priority loans and leave those other suckers behi=
nd,=E2=80=9D and they do, then they have first dibs and the other guys have=
 second dibs. If you go bankrupt and there=E2=80=99s only $60 left, then th=
e majority get 100 cents on the dollar and the minority get less than 20. B=
y not offering the deal to everyone, you can offer=C2=A0a better deal to th=
e majority.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first approach is called a pro rata debt e=
xchange, and of course there are lots of ways for it to be controversial: T=
he lenders may think that they are getting a bad deal, but that they have n=
o choice but to take it to avoid being left behind. The second approach is =
called a non-pro rata debt exchange, and is more controversial: Some lender=
s are definitely getting left behind, and will get mad and sue.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2020, Serta Simmons Bedding LLC needed some=
 extra cash, so it had some discussions with two groups of its lenders abou=
t, essentially, stiffing the other group of lenders. One group, including A=
pollo Global Management Inc. and Angelo Gordon &amp; Co., proposed putting =
some of Serta=E2=80=99s assets into a new subsidiary and and issuing new, b=
etter-collateralized loans out of that subsidiary to themselves. The other =
group, including Eaton Vance and Invesco, proposed amending the existing lo=
ans to allow higher-priority loans, and then issuing those new higher-prior=
ity loans to themselves. Serta went with the Eaton Vance proposal, stiffing=
 Apollo and Angelo Gordon.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/30998985.263439/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDctMTAvbWF0dHJlc3MtY29tcGFueS1zdGlmZnMtc29tZS1sZW5kZXJz=
P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1=
uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBd6eee7ae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  discussed this deal when it happened<=
/a>, and I wrote at the time: =E2=80=9CIt does seem like an uncomfortable p=
recedent, that a company can get some of its lenders to effectively strip c=
ollateral away from others in privately negotiated deals without offering t=
he exchange to all holders.=E2=80=9D But it happened. And now Serta=C2=A0is=
 bankrupt, there is not enough money to go around, and the investors who go=
t the new good loans are ahead of the investors who did not.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously there are lawsuits, and yesterday a =
Texas bankruptcy judge <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/30998985.263439/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vYmFua3J1cHRjeS=
1sYXcvc2VydGEtYmFua3J1cHRjeS1qdWRnZS1ibGVzc2VzLWtleS1waWVjZS1vZi1jb250ZXN0Z=
WQtZGVidC1kZWFs/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdddbbd67" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  ruled in favor=
 of Serta</a> on one key question, which is basically: Is this non-pro rata=
 exchange allowed? More technically, the loan agreement allowed Serta to bu=
y back loans =E2=80=9Con a non-pro rata basis (A) through Dutch Auctions op=
en to all Lenders holding the relevant Term Loans on a pro rata basis or (B=
) through open market purchases.=E2=80=9D Clause (A) there means that Serta=
 could offer a pro rata debt exchange to all holders, and then give the hol=
ders who agree to the exchange good new loans while stiffing the ones who d=
on=E2=80=99t. Clause (B)=C2=A0<em>arguably=C2=A0</em>means that Serta could=
 just do one-on-one exchanges with any holders it wants, though it arguably=
 doesn=E2=80=99t; the question is what =E2=80=9Copen market purchases=E2=80=
=9D means. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/30998985.263439/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnM=
vaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JhdGdIbFdXYmhfYy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBba12950a" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> Serta=E2=80=99s argument</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the context of a loan repurchas=
e, =E2=80=9Copen market=E2=80=9D means the price that a willing buyer and a=
 willing seller are able to obtain in an arms-length negotiation=E2=80=94in=
 other words, the price that Serta Simmons Bedding and any lender agreed to=
 in the =E2=80=9Copen market.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Here, Serta Simmons Bedding neg=
otiated with, and entered into, arms-length transactions in the =E2=80=9Cop=
en market=E2=80=9D with the PTL Lenders, which held a majority of Serta Sim=
mons Bedding=E2=80=99s debt, to repurchase their debt in exchange for the i=
ssuance of PTL Loans. Serta Simmons Bedding also negotiated on the open mar=
ket with the North Star Lenders, but the PTL Lenders offered better terms.<=
/p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The =E2=80=9CPTL Lenders=E2=80=9D are the majo=
rity group (Invesco, Eaton Vance, etc.); the =E2=80=9CNorth Star Lenders=E2=
=80=9D are the minority group (Angelo Gordon, Apollo, etc.). Serta=E2=80=99=
s argument is that it negotiated with everyone and chose the best deal, sti=
ffing the losing bidders, and that that=E2=80=99s allowed under the terms o=
f the credit agreement. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/30998985.263439/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bW=
VudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JLc2pvVWN4eG5QWS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB1411cc68" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> the minority lenders=E2=80=99 argument</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Unlawful Exchange Transaction was not an =
=E2=80=9Copen market purchase.=E2=80=9D It was a wholly private, exclusiona=
ry transaction=E2=80=94an exchange, at a substantial premium to market pric=
es, in which Serta handpicked a group of its lenders (excluding the remaind=
er), paid for their counsel and negotiated a complex, bespoke transaction m=
emorialized in multiple agreements running many hundreds of pages.=C2=A0 =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To characterize the Unlawful Exchange Transact=
ion as an =E2=80=9Copen market purchase=E2=80=9D would make a mockery of th=
e term, and render meaningless the requirement that all affected lenders ap=
prove changes to the <em>pro rata </em>treatment provisions of the Credit A=
greement. Indeed, if <em>this </em>is an open market purchase, then nearly =
<em>any </em>transaction would be, and the <em>pro rata </em>protections of=
 the Credit Agreement are effectively meaningless. But that is neither a lo=
gical reading of the term =E2=80=9Copen market=E2=80=9D nor a permissible i=
nterpretation of the contract. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Majority lenders cannot be permitted to conspi=
re with borrowers to bypass critical minority-lender protections which are =
expressly insulated from majority rule by requiring consent of <em>all </em=
>affected lenders; otherwise, those protections, which appear in innumerabl=
e agreements, are worthless. Permitting such a transaction would upend the =
lending markets and make it impossible for lenders to price the risk of fir=
st lien debt which could at any time be =E2=80=9Cprimed=E2=80=9D by previou=
sly <em>pari passu </em>debt owned by a mere majority of lenders under the =
guise of an =E2=80=9Copen market purchase.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Serta won. Sujeet Indap and Eric Platt at the =
Financial Times <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30=
998985.263439/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMzM2NGYwYWItMDA3My00MWEwL=
WFkNWItZjEzY2QwMmZmNTI0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5bca749b" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> report<=
/a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Federal bankruptcy judge David Jones in Housto=
n dismissed arguments by Apollo and Angelo Gordon that they had been unfair=
ly frozen out of a controversial $875mn loan refinancing Serta Simmons exec=
uted in 2020.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The slim majority of lenders that participated=
 in the deal were able to swap their debt into more senior loans, giving th=
em higher standing in the bankruptcy, while Apollo and Angelo Gordon were n=
ot. The so-called uptier exchange included $200mn of new cash lent to Serta=
 to keep it afloat during the coronavirus pandemic. Apollo and Angelo Gordo=
n are institutional investors known for their market savvy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jones said from the bench that the excluded le=
nders knew or should have known by studying the loan contract that they cou=
ld be on the wrong side of such an exchange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI sit with these matters every single=
 day,=E2=80=9D Jones said in his oral ruling. =E2=80=9CSophisticated partie=
s know what words they want to choose=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=
=89this is very easy for me.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CFor the nature of what was being tran=
sacted, this fits within [the definition] of an open market purchase,=E2=80=
=9D Jones said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jones, however, allowed a claim to proceed tha=
t said the 2020 transaction violated the so-called covenant of good faith a=
nd fair dealing, a doctrine that says a contract that may violate market no=
rms can be invalidated even if there is no official breach of explicit term=
s.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess. I don=E2=80=99t really disagree; this=
 feels to me more like an =E2=80=9Copen market purchase=E2=80=9D than not. =
The minority lenders are not wrong that there=E2=80=99s something unsettlin=
g about letting some lenders jump ahead of others in privately negotiated t=
ransactions, but that does seem to be how the market works now.</p>
