ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I have mentioned=
 before</a>, is that the customers were also very exposed to interest rates=
: In a low-rate environment, tech startups are very valuable and raise lots=
 of money and park it at SVB; in a high-rate environment, tech startups are=
 less valuable and can=E2=80=99t raise money and spend down their money at =
SVB to meet payroll. There are basically four reasons that SVB=E2=80=99s cu=
stomers might have taken money out of SVB: (1) they could get higher intere=
st rates elsewhere, (2) they needed to spend the money, (3) they read SVB=
=E2=80=99s financial statements and worried about its solvency or (4) they =
worried about other customers running on SVB so they got their own money ou=
t first. It seems like SVB=E2=80=99s customers were unusually likely to wit=
hdraw money for Reasons 2, 3 and 4: They needed more money as rates went up=
 (Reason 2), and they are more networked and pay more attention than most b=
ank depositors (Reasons 3 and 4). Meanwhile all the good customer service, =
and the loan covenants, meant that SVB=E2=80=99s customers were probably le=
ss likely than most bank depositors to take their money out to get a higher=
 rate elsewhere (Reason 1). If SVB was mostly focused on that worry =E2=80=
=94 =E2=80=9Cwill higher interest rates cause our depositors to move money =
to higher-yielding accounts elsewhere?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 it might have con=
cluded that it was fine; the other worries are what got it.</p>
</div>
